📚 Today's Goals

1. Define scientific models & theories
2. Explain how models changed (geocentric → heliocentric)
3. Identify major features of the universe
4. Use astronomical units correctly

What is a Model?

🗺️
Simplified representation of something complex

Why Use Models?

Purpose: Make complex things easier to understand
Example: Globe = Earth's shape (without every detail)
Use: Predict events, test ideas safely

What is a Theory?

🔬
Well-tested explanation based on evidence
Not a guess! Proven repeatedly through testing

Theory Example

Gravity Theory
• Explains why objects fall
• Explains planetary orbits
• Used for GPS technology
• Explains WHY, not just HOW

Model vs Theory

Model: Shows HOW (visual representation)
Theory: Explains WHY (evidence-based)

Scientific Ideas Can Change

🔄
Why? New evidence = Better understanding
• Better tools reveal new data
• Old models fit old data
• New models fit MORE data BETTER
Science self-corrects!

Old Idea: Geocentric

🌍 Earth-Centered
• Earth at center
• Everything orbits Earth
• Ptolemy (~150 AD)
• Lasted 1,400 years!

New Idea: Heliocentric

☀️ Sun-Centered
• Sun at center
• Planets orbit Sun
• Copernicus (1543)
• Galileo proved it (1610)

The Evidence

🔭
Galileo's telescope observations
• Saw Jupiter's moons orbiting Jupiter
• Not everything orbits Earth!
• Proved heliocentric model correct
Better tools → New evidence → Changed minds

What's in the Universe?

🌌
Four major features we'll explore

1. Galaxies

🌀
Definition: Massive collection of billions of stars
• Held together by gravity
• Different shapes (spiral, elliptical, irregular)
• Our galaxy: Milky Way

The Milky Way

Our home galaxy
• Spiral shape
• ~100,000 light-years across
• 200-400 billion stars

2. Stars

⭐
Definition: Hot ball of gas producing energy
• Made of hydrogen & helium
• Nuclear fusion creates light & heat
• Have life cycles (birth to death)

The Sun

Our closest star
• Medium-sized yellow star
• 4.6 billion years old
• Provides energy for Earth
⭐
The Sun

3. Solar Systems

🪐
Definition: Star with orbiting objects
• Centered around a star
• Contains planets, moons, asteroids
• Held together by gravity

Our Solar System

• Centered on the Sun
• 8 planets (including Earth)
• Formed 4.6 billion years ago
• Located in Milky Way galaxy
🪐
Solar System

4. Nebulae

☁️
Definition: Giant cloud of gas & dust
• Made of hydrogen & dust
• Birthplace of new stars
• Often colorful & beautiful

Orion Nebula

Famous star nursery
• Visible to naked eye
• 1,344 light-years away
• Active star-forming region

Smallest → Largest

🌍 Planet (thousands of km)
⭐ Star (millions of km)
🪐 Solar System (billions of km)
☁️ Nebula (light-years)
🌀 Galaxy (100,000+ light-years)
🌌 Universe (93 billion light-years)

The Distance Problem

Distance to nearest star:
40,208,000,000,000 km
These numbers are too big to work with!
Solution: Use special units

Astronomical Unit (AU)

🌍→☀️
Definition: Earth-Sun distance
• 1 AU = 150 million km
• Used for solar system distances

AU Examples

Mercury: 0.39 AU
Jupiter: 5.2 AU
Neptune: 30 AU
Pluto: 39.5 AU

Light Year

💡
Definition: Distance light travels in 1 year
• 1 light year = 9.46 trillion km
• Used for interstellar distances
• Light speed: 300,000 km/s

Light Travel Times

Sun to Earth: 8.3 minutes
Nearest star: 4.24 light-years
Milky Way center: 26,000 light-years
Looking at stars = Looking back in time!

Parsec

🔬
Definition: Professional astronomical unit
• 1 parsec = 3.26 light-years
• Used by astronomers for research
• Good for galactic distances

Which Unit to Use?

Unit Best For
AU Solar system
Light year Between stars
Parsec Galaxies & beyond

📊 Calculation Example 1

Problem: Jupiter is 5.2 AU from the Sun. How many kilometers is this?
Click to see solution steps
Step 1: Know the conversion: 1 AU = 150 million km
Step 2: Multiply: 5.2 × 150 million
Step 3: Calculate: 780 million km
Answer: 780 million kilometers

📊 Calculation Example 2

Problem: Mars is 228 million km from the Sun. How many AU is this?
Click to see solution steps
Step 1: Know the conversion: 1 AU = 150 million km
Step 2: Divide: 228 ÷ 150
Step 3: Calculate: 1.52 AU
Answer: 1.52 AU

📊 Calculation Example 3

Problem: A star is 4.2 light-years away. How many trillion km is this?
Click to see solution steps
Step 1: Know the conversion: 1 light-year ≈ 9.5 trillion km
Step 2: Multiply: 4.2 × 9.5 trillion
Step 3: Calculate: 39.9 trillion km
Answer: About 40 trillion kilometers

📊 Calculation Example 4

Problem: A nebula is 1.5 parsecs away. How many light-years is this?
Click to see solution steps
Step 1: Know the conversion: 1 parsec ≈ 3.26 light-years
Step 2: Multiply: 1.5 × 3.26
Step 3: Calculate: 4.89 light-years
Answer: About 4.9 light-years

📊 Calculation Example 5

Problem: If 1 parsec = 206,265 AU, how many AU is 0.5 parsecs?
Click to see solution steps
Step 1: Know the conversion: 1 parsec = 206,265 AU
Step 2: Multiply: 0.5 × 206,265
Step 3: Calculate: 103,132.5 AU
Answer: About 103,133 AU

📊 Calculation Example 6

Problem: Light travels at 300,000 km/s. How long does it take to travel 1 AU (150 million km)?
Click to see solution steps
Step 1: Distance = 150,000,000 km
Step 2: Speed = 300,000 km/s
Step 3: Time = Distance ÷ Speed
Step 4: 150,000,000 ÷ 300,000 = 500 seconds
Step 5: 500 seconds ÷ 60 = 8.3 minutes
Answer: 8.3 minutes

🎯 Your Turn: Practice

Challenge Problem:
Neptune is 30 AU from the Sun. Convert this to:
a) Million kilometers
b) Light-hours (hint: use light travel time)
c) Parsecs
Click to see answers
a) 30 × 150 = 4,500 million km
b) 30 × 8.3 minutes = 249 minutes = 4.15 hours
c) 30 ÷ 206,265 = 0.000145 parsecs

Milky Way Size

Diameter: ~100,000 light-years
Or: ~30,000 parsecs
That's 946,073,047,258,080,000,000 meters!
Now you see why we need special units!

Why Understanding Scale Matters

✓ Makes numbers manageable
✓ Allows meaningful comparisons
✓ Explains why we can't "just go" to stars
✓ Shows universe structure
